<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="322" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="37.[162,778,195,279]" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">
23.0, leg III 11.6, leg IV 14.8, pedipalp 6.5. Pedipalp tibia 3.2 times longer than wide (
<figureCitation box="[543,627,226,248]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="12.[142,220,1442,1461]" captionTargetBox="[144,1422,195,1408]" captionTargetId="figure-212@12.[142,1423,195,1408]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 7. A–E, male genital anatomy of Mollemeta edwardsi. A, pedipalp ventral view. B, ectal view. C, cymbial basal process. D, mesal view. E, palpal tibia. F, Metellina curtisi pedipalp ectal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5431098" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5431098/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">Fig. 7E</figureCitation>
); pedipalp as in 
<figureCitation box="[193,351,257,279]" captionStart="Figure 20" captionStartId="36.[142,220,1842,1861]" captionTargetBox="[176,1388,193,1809]" captionTargetId="figure-81@36.[176,1388,193,1809]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="Figure 20. Mollemeta edwardsi. A, female habitus. B, epigynum ventral view. C, caudal view. D, ventral view cleared. E, dorsal view cleared. F–J, male pedipalp. F, cymbium (bulb dissected). G, expanded. H, dorsal view. I, palpal tibia. J, ventral view. Scale bars 0.2 mm, except in habitus 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5431124" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5431124/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">Figure 20F–J</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[162,778,303,386]" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">
<emphasis box="[162,276,303,324]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">Variation:</emphasis>
Female total length 7.1–13.6, cephalothorax length 3.7–5.9. Male total length 5.8–8.4, cephalothorax length 2.7–4.5.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[162,778,410,555]" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">
<emphasis box="[162,593,410,431]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">
Natural history: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Álvarez-Padilla" authorityYear="2007" baseAuthorityName="Simon" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[356,593,410,431]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Mollemeta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="37" pageNumber="322" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="edwardsi">Mollemeta edwardsi</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
builds vertical orb webs on tree trunks. The web is longer than wide with 
<emphasis box="[223,234,472,493]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">c</emphasis>
. 48 radii, and several spirals of the sticky silk (more than 50). The temporary spiral is removed and the hub is closed (
<figureCitation box="[372,471,533,555]" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="16.[142,220,1706,1725]" captionTargetBox="[304,1262,195,1673]" captionTargetId="figure-80@16.[302,1262,195,1673]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Figure 10. Photos of webs: A, Allende puyehuensis. B, Chrysometa acinosa. C, Mollemeta edwardsi. D, Metabus ebanoverde. Scale lines 10 cm. Photos A–C from Puyehue National Park, Chile. Photo D from Ebano Verde Scientific Reserve, Dominican Republic. (Photos A to C by G. Hormiga)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5431104" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5431104/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">Fig. 10C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[162,778,579,785]" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">
<emphasis box="[162,322,579,600]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">Phylogenetics:</emphasis>
The monotypy of this genus is based on the cladistic placement of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Álvarez-Padilla" authorityYear="2007" baseAuthorityName="Simon" baseAuthorityYear="1904" box="[486,627,609,631]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Mollemeta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="37" pageNumber="322" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="edwardsi">
<emphasis box="[486,627,609,631]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">M. edwardsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as sister to a clade that contains the genera 
<taxonomicName box="[585,642,641,662]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Meta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="37" pageNumber="322" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[585,642,641,662]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">Meta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chamberlin &amp; Ivie" authorityYear="1941" box="[663,771,640,661]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Metellina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="37" pageNumber="322" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[663,771,640,661]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">Metellina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="O.Pickard-Cambridge" authorityYear="1869" box="[162,328,671,692]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Dolichognatha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="37" pageNumber="322" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[162,328,671,692]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">Dolichognatha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[351,437,671,692]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Allende" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="37" pageNumber="322" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[351,437,671,692]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">Allende</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1894" box="[513,648,671,692]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Chrysometa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="37" pageNumber="322" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[513,648,671,692]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">Chrysometa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Figs 1,2). Autapomorphies of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Álvarez-Padilla" authorityYear="2007" box="[402,521,701,722]" class="Arachnida" family="Tetragnathidae" genus="Mollemeta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="37" pageNumber="322" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[402,521,701,722]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">Mollemeta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the ring-shaped cymbium, and the unique shape of the conductor and embolus (
<figureCitation box="[273,389,763,785]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="12.[142,220,1442,1461]" captionTargetBox="[144,1422,195,1408]" captionTargetId="figure-212@12.[142,1423,195,1408]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 7. A–E, male genital anatomy of Mollemeta edwardsi. A, pedipalp ventral view. B, ectal view. C, cymbial basal process. D, mesal view. E, palpal tibia. F, Metellina curtisi pedipalp ectal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5431098" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5431098/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">Fig. 7A, B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[162,446,809,831]" box="[162,446,809,831]" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">
<emphasis box="[162,310,809,830]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">Composition:</emphasis>
Monotypic.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="37.[162,777,855,908]" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">
<emphasis box="[162,307,855,876]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">Distribution:</emphasis>
This species is endemic to 
<collectingCountry box="[716,777,855,877]" name="Chile" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">Chile</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[170,269,885,908]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="17.[162,240,1348,1367]" captionTargetBox="[162,1442,195,1316]" captionTargetId="figure-278@17.[162,1443,195,1316]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figure 11. Distribution maps: A, Metabus species, Central and northern South America. B, Allende species, Chile. C, Chrysometa species, Chile. D, Mollemeta edwardsi, Chile." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5431106" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5431106/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="322">Fig. 11D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
